# Chapter 8 — Canonicalization

Big word. Small idea.

**Canonicalization means: one value, one byte string.**

You read a slat, write it out canonically, and every writer produces
the same bytes. Two writers on two machines producing the same value
produce the same bytes. Two records with the same fields in different
orders produce the same bytes.

Once you have that property, you can content-address (Chapter 9), you
can sign (Chapter 10), you can Merkle-attest a corpus (Chapter 10),
you can trust the substrate.

Without it, you have JSON's fifteen-year-old problem: `{\"a\":1,\"b\":2}`
and `{\"b\":2,\"a\":1}` are the same value but different bytes, so
signatures don't match, hashes don't match, caches don't hit, and
signing standards had to invent JCS (RFC 8785) to try to fix it.

SLAT bakes canonicalization into the writer. No extra step. No
opt-in.

## The eleven rules

Every canonical slat obeys eleven rules. I'll walk each one with a
tiny example.

## Rule 1 — head first

The `_form` symbol goes immediately after `(`.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps '(event :ts 1 :kind \"card.opened\"))
```

Produces `(event :kind \"card.opened\" :ts 1)`. Head `event` at position
0.

## Rule 2 — positional next

Positional values come after the head, before the keyword pairs.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps '(log :level :warn \"message here\" iter-350))
```

The reader parsed `\"message here\"` and `iter-350` as positional. The
writer emits them right after the head. In your text, that would look
like:

```
(log \"message here\" iter-350 :level :warn)
```

Except — actually, canonical form has keys sorted lexicographically
(rule 3). So positional and keys mix based on the rule, not the
reader order. In practice the canonical form is:

```
(log \"message here\" iter-350 :level :warn)
```

## Rule 3 — keywords sorted

`:keyword value` pairs are sorted by keyword name in lexicographic byte
order (UTF-8).

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps '(event :ts 1 :by 'motoi :kind \"card.opened\"))
```

Produces:

```
(event :by 'motoi :kind \"card.opened\" :ts 1)
```

`:by` before `:kind` before `:ts`. Alphabetical.

Every writer everywhere sorts the same way. That's what makes signing
work.

## Rule 4 — comments dropped from canonical

`_comment` fields are not signed material. The canonical form is the
signed form. If you want to sign a comment, promote it to a keyword.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps '(event :ts 1 :kind \"card.opened\"))
```

...regardless of what comments were attached to the source, produces
just the record. No comment.

If you want the comment to be part of the record forever:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps '(event :ts 1 :kind \"card.opened\" :note \"the first card\"))
```

Now `:note` is a keyword, part of the record, part of the canonical
form, part of what gets signed.

## Rule 5 — strings normalized

UTF-8, NFC (Normalized Form C — canonical composition). The five
escapes are `\\n \\t \\r \\\\ \\\"`. No other characters are escaped. Any
code point ≥ 0x20 outside those five is emitted literally.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps \"hi\\nthere\")
```

Produces `\"hi\\nthere\"` — the newline is escaped.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps \"🌸\")
```

Produces `\"🌸\"` — the cherry blossom is emitted literally, not as
`ἳ8`.

## Rule 6 — numbers

- Integers: decimal, no leading zeros.
- Rationals: reduced to lowest terms.
- Bigdecimals: canonical decimal string with trailing `M`.
- Floats: shortest round-trip representation.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps 3.14)
```

Produces `3.14`. Not `3.140000000000000124344978758017532527446746826171875`.
The shortest string that round-trips through IEEE-754 to the same
float.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps 2/6)
```

Produces `1/3`. Reduced. Always.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps (fraction 10 30))
```

Also `1/3`.

## Rule 7 — booleans and nil

`#t`, `#f`, `nil`. No aliases. No `true`/`false`. No `null`.

## Rule 8 — instants

ISO-8601 with UTC (`Z` suffix). No fractional seconds unless present
in source.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps (slat-loads \"#inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00-05:00\\\"\"))
```

Produces `#inst \"2026-07-11T23:22:00Z\"`. Normalized to UTC.

Fractional seconds preserve as-is. If the source has milliseconds, the
canonical form has milliseconds. If it doesn't, it doesn't.

## Rule 9 — bytes

Base64 without padding.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps (slat-loads \"#b64 \\\"SGVsbG8=\\\"\"))
```

Produces `#b64 \"SGVsbG8\"`. Trailing `=` dropped.

## Rule 10 — whitespace

Single space between tokens. No leading or trailing whitespace inside
parens. Single trailing newline at the end of `.slatl` lines. No
trailing newline inside `.slat` documents.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-dumps '(event   :ts   1))
```

Produces `(event :ts 1)`. Extra whitespace collapsed.

## Rule 11 — no structural sharing

If a slat has `#0=` labels and `#0#` references, the canonical writer
expands them before emitting.

```
(pair #0=(a b c) #0#)
```

...becomes:

```
(pair (a b c) (a b c))
```

The signed form is always fully expanded. This prevents an attacker
from crafting a small labeled payload that expands to a huge tree at
read time, then signing the small form and shipping the expansion.

The reader still accepts `#0=` and `#0#` — the guard is on canonical
output, not input.

## The one-value one-byte-string property

Once you have all eleven rules, this holds:

```motoi-scheme
(define v '(event :ts 1 :kind \"card.opened\" :by 'motoi))
(define bytes-a (slat-dumps v))
(define bytes-b (slat-dumps (slat-loads (slat-dumps v))))
(equal? bytes-a bytes-b)
```

`#t`. Always.

The property holds across bindings too:

```
JavaScript:  slat.dumps(v)  → \"(event :by 'motoi :kind \\\"card.opened\\\" :ts 1)\"
Python:      slat.dumps(v)  → b\"(event :by 'motoi :kind \\\"card.opened\\\" :ts 1)\"
```

Byte-for-byte identical. That's the CI gate.

## Why we care

Three reasons.

**One: content addressing.** A value has one canonical byte string.
The sha256 of that byte string is the value's content ID. Two writers
producing the same value produce the same content ID. That's how
deduplication works. That's how the atom store recognizes when two
authors write the same atom.

**Two: signing.** You sign the canonical bytes. Any receiver
canonicalizes their copy, hashes, compares to the signature. If the
canonicalization is stable across writers, the signature verifies.

**Three: caching.** A cache keyed on content ID hits whenever any
writer produced the same value. Two authors writing the same fact
share one cache line.

## Non-canonical output

Bindings may emit non-canonical output when the caller doesn't request
canonical form. `slat-dumps` returns canonical form. `slat-dumps-pretty`
returns pretty-printed non-canonical.

Non-canonical output is fine for humans. For signing, hashing, or any
byte-level operation, use canonical.

## Try this

Write the same record with keys in different orders. Compare the
canonical bytes.

```motoi-scheme
(define a (slat-loads \"(event :ts 1 :kind \\\"card.opened\\\" :by 'motoi)\"))
(define b (slat-loads \"(event :by 'motoi :ts 1 :kind \\\"card.opened\\\")\"))
(define c (slat-loads \"(event :kind \\\"card.opened\\\" :by 'motoi :ts 1)\"))

(equal? (slat-dumps a) (slat-dumps b) (slat-dumps c))
```

`#t`. Three records. One canonical form.

Round-trip a value ten times.

```motoi-scheme
(define original '(atom :id \"atm-001\" :type 'code :weight 1.0 :body '(lambda (x) x)))
(define (roundtrip v n)
  (if (= n 0) v (roundtrip (slat-loads (slat-dumps v)) (- n 1))))

(equal? (slat-dumps original) (slat-dumps (roundtrip original 10)))
```

`#t`. Ten round-trips. Same bytes.

## The canonicalization rules in one page

For quick reference, here's the whole list:

1. Head first.
2. Positional after the head.
3. Keywords sorted lexicographically by name.
4. Comments dropped.
5. Strings UTF-8 NFC with only the five standard escapes.
6. Numbers in normalized form (integers decimal, rationals reduced,
   bigdecimals with `M`, floats shortest round-trip).
7. Booleans `#t`/`#f`, nil is `nil`.
8. Instants ISO-8601 UTC.
9. Bytes base64 no padding.
10. Whitespace single-spaced, no trailing.
11. No structural sharing.

Appendix D has each rule with more examples. Chapter 9 uses the
canonical form to build content addresses. Chapter 10 uses content
addresses to build signatures. Every rule in this chapter enables the
next two.

## Where next

Chapter 9 — content addressing. Now that we have canonical bytes,
we can sha256 them to get a stable fingerprint. Any value, one
fingerprint, forever. The Cortex uses these for deduplication. The
training corpus uses them for provenance.

